      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Public Pays</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Fred Averick says James Shreeve's June 27 Op-Ed on necessity of genetic research glosses over financial costs of such research, which is mostly paid for by public</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Where the Genome Leads Us,'' by James Shreeve (Op-Ed, June 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Where the Genome Leads Us,'' by James Shreeve (Op-Ed, June 27):</p>
        <p>Mr. Shreeve rightly points out that ''scientists need a version of the genome to work with now,'' but he glosses over the financial costs by saying it will ''cost drug companies a few million dollars a year and university researchers a little grant money.''</p>
        <p>But to whom will the drug companies pass this ''few million dollars'' cost? Certainly not the stockholders.</p>
        <p>And the majority of research grant money at universities comes from the government. Where do they get their money from?</p>
        <p>FRED AVERICK  New York, June 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
